<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1324,479,785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
REMARKS. The original description serves to identify this species very well. An additional character not mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hesse" box="[666,823,519,545]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refString="Hesse, A. J. (1967) Additions to the Cyrtosiinae (Bombyliidae) of South Africa. Annals of the South African Museum, 50, 89 - 130." type="journal article" year="1967">
Hesse (
<number box="[752,813,519,545]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1967.0">1967</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
that can help distinguish this species from its congeners is the yellowish white frons (
<figureCitation box="[760,830,559,585]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 ­ 4" captionStartId="3.[264,383,1636,1660]" captionTargetBox="[538,1056,531,1616]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[538,1056,529,1616]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 ­ 4. Onchopelma, dorsal view (wings removed), showing color pattern of head, thorax, and abdomen. 1. O. brevifasciatum, sp. n., male. 2. O. brevifasciatum, sp. n., female. 3. O. irwini, sp. n., female. 4. O. karooanum Hesse, female paratype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156143/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[814,830,559,585]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
) (black color extending from occiput only to lateral ocelli of ocellar triangle). Since the original description, only one additional specimen of this species has been found: a headless female from Merweville, 
<collectingCountry name="South Africa" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">South Africa</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
